Defines the `ctx-scan` CLI surface (via `clap`) and the dispatch logic that routes a parsed `Cli` to one of five mutually exclusive behaviors: full scan, `--dry-run`, `--check`, `--update`, or `--stop-hook`. This is the only place command-line flags are declared, so any new runner mode needs a matching flag/field here plus a `conflicts_with` entry to keep the mutual-exclusion invariant intact.

The `Mode` sub-struct (`dry_run`, `check`, `update`) is flattened into `Cli` and enforces exclusivity via clap's `conflicts_with`/`conflicts_with_all`; `stop_hook` is separately marked conflicting with all three. `Cli` exposes only accessor methods (`dry_run()`, `check()`, `update()`, `stop_hook()`, `dir()`, `prompts()`) â€” fields are private, so callers outside this file must go through these. `prompts` is resolved against the process cwd, not the scanned `dir`, which matters if callers assume path-relativity.

Key entry points: `list_targets`, `check`, `stop_hook`, and `dispatch` each take a generic `W: Write` for output, making them independently testable against an in-memory buffer rather than real stdout. `dispatch<A: Agent, W: Write>(agent: &A, cli: &Cli, out: &mut W)` is the main production path â€” it validates the dir, then branches on `cli.update()` to call `update_run` (selective rebuild) vs. `scan_run` (full scan), delegating actual work to `crate::runner`. `stop_hook` is the Claude Code Stop-hook integration: it never calls the agent (regeneration is deliberately deferred to post-session `--update`, since the Stop event fires per-turn not per-session), always fail-opens on error at the binary level, and emits a `{"systemMessage": ...}` JSON line only when the tree is stale â€” silent on a fresh tree. Its message text, built by `staleness_message`, pre-appends `--approve` to the suggested command when `changed_files.len() > ctx_summarize::runner::MAX_TARGETS`, so the suggested fix-it command never dead-ends on the cost gate.

`validate_dir` canonicalizes and requires `dir.is_dir()`, returning `ScanError::DirNotFound`/`ScanError::Io` â€” every public function here calls it first. Output rendering (`render`, `render_staleness`) defines the plaintext wire format consumers might parse: `leaves:`/`rollups:`/`readme:` counts for a full scan, and `fresh` or `stale-dir:`/`stale-leaf:`/`orphan-leaf:` lines for staleness reports â€” changing these labels affects any script scraping CLI output. Depends on `ctx_summarize::agent::Agent` (trait dispatched generically, not dynamically) and `ctx_summarize::runner::MAX_TARGETS` (the shared cost-gate constant, not redefined locally).